# WHAT IT IS
#   `fido-key-manager` is **the Rust ecosystem's reference CLI tool
#   for managing FIDO / CTAP 2.x security keys** (YubiKey 5 series,
#   YubiKey 5C NFC, SoloKey 2, Trussed-based tokens, Feitian K9 /
#   K28, OnlyKey, Nitrokey 3, NitroKey FIDO2, Token2, GoTrust Idem,
#   any other CTAP2.0/2.1/2.2 compliant authenticator).  It speaks
#   the **CTAP 2.x wire protocol** directly to the device over USB
#   HID, NFC, or Bluetooth LE — bypassing the OS authenticator UI
#   entirely — to:
#
#     • Enumerate connected tokens and dump their capabilities
#       (supported transports, supported PIN protocols, max
#       credentials supported, available algorithms, available
#       extensions, current PIN retry counter)
#
#     • Set, change, and policy-enforce PIN codes
#       (minimum-length policy, RPID-restricted minPinLength
#       extension policy, force-change-on-next-use flag)
#
#     • Enroll, rename, and delete biometric (fingerprint)
#       templates on biometric-equipped tokens
#
#     • Enumerate every discoverable credential stored on the
#       token (filtered by RPID or RPID hash), update credential
#       user metadata (display name + name), and delete
#       credentials
#
#     • Toggle Always-Require-User-Verification mode + enable the
#       Enterprise Attestation extension
#
#     • Factory-reset a token (must be done within 10 seconds of
#       plug-in; USB-HID transport only on multi-interface tokens)
#
#     • Vendor-specific commands:
#         · SoloKey 2 / Trussed:  solo-key-info, solo-key-random
#         · YubiKey:               yubikey-get-config
#         · USB tokens:            wink (visible-LED flash)
#
#   Built with feature flags `usb` (default), `nfc` (default),
#   `bluetooth` (opt-in; flakey on Linux/Windows), `solokey`
#   (vendor commands), `yubikey` (vendor commands).
#
# CLI ARGUMENT GRAMMAR  (verbatim from fido-key-manager/src/main.rs
#                       clap derive `Opt` enum + per-subcommand
#                       arg structs; extracted via
#                       raw.githubusercontent.com fetch of
#                       fido-key-manager/src/main.rs)
#
#   fido-key-manager <COMMAND>
#
#   Commands:
#     selection                      Request user presence on a
#                                    connected FIDO token
#     info [OPTIONS]                 Show information about all
#                                    connected FIDO tokens
#         --watch                    Continue watching for
#                                    connected devices until
#                                    explicitly terminated
#                                    (Ctrl + C)
#     factory-reset                  Reset the connected FIDO token
#                                    to factory settings, deleting
#                                    all keys
#     toggle-always-uv               Toggle the "Always Require
#                                    User Verification" feature
#     enable-enterprise-attestation  Enable the "Enterprise
#                                    Attestation" feature
#     bio-info [OPTIONS]             Get information about
#                                    biometric authentication
#         --watch                    Continue watching for devices
#     enroll-fingerprint [NAME]      Enroll a fingerprint
#                                    NAME: human-readable label
#                                          (e.g. 'left thumb')
#     list-fingerprints              List all enrolled fingerprints
#     rename-fingerprint <ID> <NAME> Rename an enrolled fingerprint
#     remove-fingerprint <ID>...     Remove enrolled fingerprint(s)
#     set-pin-policy [OPTIONS]       Set policies for PINs (must
#                                    specify at least one of
#                                    --length / --rpids /
#                                    --force-change)
#         -l, --length <N>           Minimum PIN length in Unicode
#                                    codepoints
#         -r, --rpids <RPID>         RPIDs authorised to use the
#                                    `minPinLength` extension
#                                    (may be specified multiple
#                                     times)
#         --force-change             Invalidate the existing PIN,
#                                    forcing change before token
#                                    can be used again
#     set-pin -n <PIN>               Set a PIN on a token that
#                                    does not already have one
#         -n, --new-pin <PIN>        New PIN value
#     change-pin -o <PIN> -n <PIN>   Change a PIN on a token that
#                                    already has a PIN set
#         -o, --old-pin <PIN>        Old PIN value
#         -n, --new-pin <PIN>        New PIN value
#     get-credential-metadata        Get discoverable-credential
#                                    storage metadata
#     list-credentials [OPTIONS]     List discoverable credentials
#                                    (no filter = all)
#         --rpid <RPID>              Filter by relying-party ID
#         --hash <HEX>               Filter by SHA-256 hash of RPID
#                                    (mutually exclusive with --rpid)
#     delete-credential <CRED_ID>    Delete a discoverable credential
#                                    (CRED_ID is hex-encoded bytes)
#     update-credential-user <CRED_ID> <USER_ID> [OPTIONS]
#                                    Update user info for a credential
#                                    (CRED_ID + USER_ID are hex bytes;
#                                     must specify at least --name /
#                                     --display-name)
#         --name <NAME>              Human-palatable username /
#                                    email / phone
#         --display-name <NAME>      Human-palatable display name
#     solo-key-info [--watch]        SoloKey 2 / Trussed info
#                                    (feature: solokey)
#     solo-key-random                Get random bytes from a
#                                    SoloKey 2 / Trussed device
#                                    (feature: solokey)
#     yubikey-get-config             Get a YubiKey's config
#                                    (feature: yubikey)
#     wink [--watch]                 Wink a connected USB device
#                                    (feature: usb)
#
#   Standard clap auto-flags  (always available):
#     -h, --help                     Show help
#     -V, --version                  Print version
#
# AXIS / CORPUS POSITION
#   `fido-key-manager` is a workspace member of `kanidm/webauthn-rs`
#   and declares **direct** dependencies on `webauthn-authenticator-
#   rs` (the client/authenticator-side crate of the workspace) and
#   `webauthn-rs-core` (the protocol type layer) — both ARE the
#   canonical Rust WebAuthn stack.  Verified via `gh api repos/
#   kanidm/webauthn-rs/contents/fido-key-manager/Cargo.toml`.
#
#   `kanidm/webauthn-rs` is THE canonical Rust WebAuthn /  FIDO2 /
#   CTAP2 protocol stack — the production-grade Rust implementation
#   of:
#
#     • W3C WebAuthn Level 3 (the browser-server JavaScript API
#       spec — `navigator.credentials.create()` /
#       `.get()` round-trip; the Rust crate `webauthn-rs` implements
#       the **server / relying-party** side of this protocol, with
#       typed `Webauthn::new_unsafe_experts_only()` /
#       `WebauthnBuilder::new(rp_id, rp_origins).build()` /
#       `webauthn.start_passkey_registration(user_unique_id,
#       user_name, user_display_name, exclude_credentials)
#       -> CreationChallengeResponse` /
#       `webauthn.finish_passkey_registration(reg, &state)
#       -> Passkey` /
#       `webauthn.start_passkey_authentication(&[passkey])
#       -> RequestChallengeResponse` /
#       `webauthn.finish_passkey_authentication(auth, &state)
#       -> AuthenticationResult` typed builder API)
#
#     • FIDO CTAP 2.0 (Client to Authenticator Protocol — the
#       wire-format between a client (browser, OS, this CLI) and
#       the hardware authenticator over USB HID / NFC / BLE),
#       FIDO CTAP 2.1 (PIN protocols + biometric enrollment +
#       enterprise attestation + minPinLength extension), FIDO
#       CTAP 2.2 (preview) implementations  — the workspace's
#       `webauthn-authenticator-rs` crate is **the canonical Rust
#       implementation of the entire CTAP wire protocol**, with
#       typed `Ctap20Authenticator` / `Ctap21Authenticator` /
#       `Ctap21PreAuthenticator` enum dispatching, typed
#       `AnyTransport` (the cross-transport dispatcher selecting
#       between USB HID via `hidapi`, NFC via PC/SC, Bluetooth LE
#       via `btleplug`), typed CBOR-encoded request/response
#       schemas for every CTAP command (`authenticator_get_info`,
#       `authenticator_make_credential`,
#       `authenticator_get_assertion`,
#       `authenticator_get_next_assertion`,
#       `authenticator_reset`, `authenticator_client_pin`,
#       `authenticator_bio_enrollment`,
#       `authenticator_credential_management`,
#       `authenticator_config`, `authenticator_selection`,
#       `authenticator_large_blobs`)
#
#     • FIDO Metadata Service v3 (the canonical authenticator
#       attestation database; the workspace's `webauthn-
#       attestation-ca-list` crate auto-ingests the FIDO Alliance's
#       signed metadata BLOB and exposes it as typed
#       `AttestationCaList` entries for use in TPM / packed /
#       packed-self / fido-u2f / android-key / android-safetynet
#       / apple / none attestation statement verification)
#
#     • COSE algorithm registry (the workspace's `webauthn-rs-
#       core` crate exposes the typed `COSEKey` /
#       `COSEKeyType::EC_EC2 / RSA / Ed25519 / OKP / Symmetric`
#       enum, the typed `COSEAlgorithm::ES256 / ES384 / ES512 /
#       PS256 / PS384 / PS512 / RS256 / RS384 / RS512 / EdDSA`
#       algorithm enum, and round-trip CBOR encoding /
#       decoding for every COSE key type)
